ğŸ” What is Binary Search?
Binary Search is used when you have a sorted array or you can apply monotonic logic (i.e., answer becomes better/worse as you move right). You repeatedly cut the search space in half â€” hence O(log n) time.

ğŸ§  When to Use Binary Search?
Look for these clues in the problem:

ğŸ’¬ If the problem says...	ğŸ’¡ Think of Binary Search on...
"Find in sorted array"	âœ… Sorted array
"Minimum/Maximum possible value"	âœ… Binary Search on answer (value space)
"Kth element / peak / rotation / closest"	âœ… Modified binary search (conditions)
"Is it possible to...?"	âœ… Search on result not the array

âš™ï¸ Types of Binary Search
Type	Description	Time
ğŸ¯ Basic Binary Search	Find exact element in sorted array	O(log n)
ğŸ”„ Lower/Upper Bound	First â‰¥ target / last â‰¤ target	O(log n)
ğŸ§® Binary Search on Answer	Find min/max value that satisfies a condition	O(log(max))

âœ¨ Code Template (Classic)
java
Copy
Edit
int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target) {
    int low = 0, high = arr.length - 1;

    while (low <= high) {
        int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

        if (arr[mid] == target) return mid;
        else if (arr[mid] < target) low = mid + 1;
        else high = mid - 1;
    }

    return -1; // not found
}
